    <worksheet name='Surah Size Treemap.'>
      <layout-options>
        <caption>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>What this treemap reveals at a glance:</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>Meccan surahs (blue) are more numerous but individually smaller</run>
            <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'> — there are many small blue rectangles. These are the shorter, more poetic surahs focused on faith fundamentals.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>Medinan surahs (orange) are fewer but massive</run>
            <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'> — Al-Baqara dominates the entire right side. The Medinan surahs (revealed after migration to Medina) tend to be longer because they deal with legislation, governance, and community matters.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>By total word count, Meccan and Medinan are roughly comparable</run>
            <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'> — despite Mecca having 86 surahs vs Medina&apos;s 28, the Medinan surahs&apos; length compensates. The blue and orange areas look close to 50/50.</run>
            <run>
Surah Name.  
Color shows details about Revelation Place.  
Size shows sum of Word Count.  
The marks are labeled by Surah Name.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </caption>
      </layout-options>
      <table>
        <view>
          <datasources>
            <datasource caption='quran_surahs' name='federated.0nyq5lu1vpdke31952giy10rt0ck' />
          </datasources>
